name: 1-tetradecanethiol
Reason: The basic unit for comparison is methane, which has a melting point of -182.5 degrees Celsius. The elongation of the carbon chain generally increases the melting point due to increased van der Waals forces and surface area allowing for better packing. Each additional methylene group (CH2) typically contributes an increase of approximately 2 degrees Celsius to the melting point. As there are 13 additional carbons in the chain of 1-tetradecanethiol, this would account for an increase of 26 degrees Celsius. Additionally, the presence of the thiol (SH) group introduces the possibility of hydrogen bonding, which generally raises the melting point compared to hydrocarbons. However, the effect of this on the melting point is relatively small due to the single hydrogen bond donor, so it might contribute an additional increase of approximately 5 degrees Celsius.
